The two Poland
The European Parliament recently condemned the Polish government's attempt to strip Bronislaw Geremek of his parliamentary mandate.
A former leader of Solidarity, a former political prisoner, and a former foreign minister - he led Poland's accession to NATO - Geremek refused to sign another declaration stating that he was not a secret police agent at the time of communism.
European parliamentarians spoke of a "witch hunt" in relation to the behavior of the Polish government, and Geremek stated that the lustration law [décommunisation] constitutes a threat to public freedoms.
In response, Polish Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski accused him of "harming the motherland" and stirring up anti-Polish sentiment.
The communists used the same words when Geremek criticized their abuse of power.
A constitutional court decision dated May 11 largely invalidated the lustration law, allowing Geremek to retain his seat in the European Parliament, at least for now.
However, this law is part of a broader policy of the Polish government, which has no other aim than to weaken the country's institutions and democratic fabric.
What is happening in Poland, a country where the collapse of communism began?
Each revolution goes through two phases: first, a fight for freedom, and then a struggle for power.
The first is a liberation of the human soul by which man expresses what is best in him, while the second frees the worst: envy, intrigue, avarice, suspicion, and the desire for vengeance.
The revolution sparked by the Polish trade union Solidarity followed an unusual trajectory.
Solidarity, forced into clandestinity when martial law was declared in December 1981, survived seven years of repression to reappear in the open in 1989, in the wake of Gorbachev's "perestroika" initiative.
During the negotiations that brought an end to the communist regime, Solidarity and the reformist wing of the communist government reached a compromise that paved the way for the peaceful dismantling of the communist dictatorship throughout the Soviet bloc.
Solidarity adopted a compromising attitude rather than one of vengeance, preferring the idea of a Poland for all rather than a country divided between all-powerful winners and oppressed losers.
Since 1989, there have been changes in government, but the country has remained stable. The former communists themselves have accepted the rules of parliamentary democracy and market economy.
But not everyone followed this path.
Today, Poland is governed by a coalition of post-Solidarity revanchists, post-communist provincial troublemakers, xenophobic and anti-Semitic groups, heirs to pre-war chauvinism, and the circles surrounding Radio Maryja, voice of ethno-clerical fundamentalism.
Alarming signs can be seen everywhere: the authority of the judiciary is being eroded, the independence of the Constitutional Tribunal is being questioned, officials are being bribed, and the prosecutor's office is being politicized.
Every day, social life is subject to repressive regulation.
Why all this?
Every successful revolution has its winners and losers.
The Polish revolution brought public freedoms, but also more delinquency, a market economy, as well as the risks of bankruptcy for businesses and high unemployment, along with the emergence of a dynamic middle class, accompanied by a widening income gap.
It opened Poland to Europe, but it also induced fear of the foreigner and fear of a mass invasion of Western culture.
For the losers of the 1989 Polish revolution, freedom is accompanied by many uncertainties.
In large corporations, Solidarity workers have become victims of the freedoms they conquered.
In the communist prison universe, people were considered to belong to the state, but the state took care of them.
In a world of freedom, there is no one to take care of us.
It is in this atmosphere of anxiety that the current government governs, combining George Bush's conservative potion with Vladimir Putin's centralism.
The Solidarity veterans thought that the end of the dictatorship would allow them to reach the pinnacle.
But the guilty among the communists were not punished, and the virtuous militants of Solidarity were not rewarded.
Also, the feeling of injustice gave birth to resentment, envy, and a vengeful energy directed both at the old enemies and the old friends who seemed to be getting away with it.
The losers did not want to acknowledge that the conquest of freedom was Poland's greatest success in 300 years.
For them, Poland remained a country governed by the communist security apparatus.
This Poland lacked a moral revolution that would make crimes not go unpunished, virtue be rewarded, and injustices be rectified.
After their victory in the 2005 general elections, the political parties of the losers chose a method: a large purge.
According to initial estimates, lustration was expected to take 17 years and affect 700,000 people.
A list of names was found in the security service archives; it will be made public.
And the 700,000 people promised lustration must declare that they did not collaborate with the security services.
Those who refuse or make a false declaration must be fired and barred from practicing their profession for ten years.

Cardinal Dziwisz of Krakow reminds us that there is no place "for revenge, vengeance, lack of respect for human dignity, and baseless accusations".
Never since the fall of communism has a cardinal used such strong words.
Should this lustration have taken place at the beginning of Poland's transformation? The goal of this peaceful revolution was freedom, sovereignty, and economic reforms, not a hunt for suspects, whether proven or not, of having belonged to the secret police.
If this hunt had been organized in 1990, neither Leszek Balcerowicz's economic reforms nor the establishment of the rule of law would have been possible.
And Poland would not be a member of NATO or the European Union.
Today, two Poland's are facing each other.
The Poland of suspicion, fear, and vengeance is fighting the Poland of hope, courage, and dialogue.
This Poland - made of openness and tolerance, the one of John Paul II and Czeslaw Milisz, of my friends from the underground and prison - must prevail.
I believe that the Poles will once again defend their right to be treated with dignity.
The Constitutional Tribunal's decision gives hope that the second phase of the Polish revolution will not destroy what gave birth to it, the desire for freedom, nor what it has generated, a democratic state.
